passages.text: Earnings review: 2Q25 GM miss; even softer 2025 growth outlook; maintain Neutral
6415.TW 12m Price Target: NT\\$315.00 Price: NT\\$308.50 Upside: 2.1%

Silergy hosted its 2Q25 analyst meeting on Aug 29. 2Q25 core operation results were largely in line with GSe, yet lower vs. Bloomberg consensus. On margin side, 2Q25 GM (51.5%, down 241bps QoQ) came in lower vs. GSe/cons. of 53.9%/54% due to unfavorable product mix and heightened production cost, while Opex ratio of 39.5% was lower vs. GSe/cons. of 41.9%/40.6% thanks to better cost control. On a proforma basis (excludes inventory write off), 2Q25 GM decline to 52.4% (vs 54.9% in 1Q25) and 2Q25 OpM recover to 19.6% (vs. 17.1% in 1Q25) post one- off employee bonus expense in 1Q25.

During the analyst call, management toned down its 2025 full- year revenue growth outlook and said it will be unable to achieve its 20- 30% of growth target for this year, yet still expects to deliver positive YoY growth. Moreover, the company is now only looking for a flat to slightly up QoQ revenue growth in 3Q25, which came in largely below GSe/cons. of 21%/22% QoQ growth; with GM to maintain at 52- 54%. Management explained that the weakness is primarily due to weaker- than- expected demand and delays in new project ramp- ups, impacted by tariff uncertainties and more conservative client behavior, particularly among those with significant exposures to US end- demand.

Nevertheless, Sergy remains confident in its ability to return to 20- 30% YoY revenue growth in the future once uncertainties subside supported by contributions from new product launches, as evidenced by its current design- in/win. For full- year 2025E, we now model revenue to grow 1.2% YoY (vs. 14.2% previously), with GM at 52.7% (vs. 53.9% previously).

We maintain our cautious view on SilergyWe believe Silergy is experiencing near- term market share loss compared to its mainland China competitors. Note that Silergy's revenue only up \(2\%\) YoY as of 1H25 vs an avg. growth of \(31.8\%\) of mainland China peers (Exhibit 2). Nevertheless, with a smaller revenue scale we expect operating deleveraging to hamper its bottom line. Overall, we maintain a Neutral rating on the stock, as we anticipate that new project ramp- ups will require additional time to deliver meaningful results, with server exposure still limited and only expected to scale more significantly from 2027 onward. Coupled with recent conservative client behavior dampening the growth outlook, we believe clearer evidence of market share recovery and a more substantial ramp- up in revenue from high- growth segments (e.g., auto, AI server) are necessary for a re- rating; we thus maintain our Neutral rating.

We revise down our 12- month TP to NT\\$315 from NT\\$365, still based on an unchanged target P/E of 22x (benchmarked to 0.5stdv. below 10- year average of 32x) to our 2026E EPS, and discounted back to 2025E at \(13.4\%\) CoE (unchanged). Our CoE is based on data from Bloomberg, with key assumptions (all unchanged) including (1) 1.5x beta, (2) \(4.0\%\) risk free rate, and (3) a market risk premium at \(6.25\%\) (in line with GS house view). Our new 12- month TP implies c. \(2.1\%\) upside potential from the current share price (vs. avg. coverage upside of c. \(9.3\%\) ), and we thus maintain Silergy at Neutral rating.

Silergy is a leading local PMIC (power management IC) design house. While we like Silergy's long- term growth story with continuous expansion into higher end segment such as server/data center, HPC, automotive, we still have concerns over 1) competition landscape, 2) pace of end demand recovery, 3) possible tariffs. We still see a severe competition from TI and mainland China local PMIC (power management IC) peers. As for overall demand, while we do expect a cyclical recovery in 2025 as inventory is further digested in the system, we are uncertain about the pace of recovery as we see inventory still at relatively high levels across key IDMs. Furthermore, we are also concerned about the impact to end demand from possible tariffs.

Silergy is now trading largely in line with its 5- year average P/E based on FY25E EPS, which we view as fair given the ongoing overhang from the competition from mainland China and Texas Instruments. We thus have a Neutral rating on Silergy.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
